(15. People get confused when language implementations break language guarantees) Tj
T*
(Source: Computer Things | Published: Tue, 21 Apr 2026 17:40:17 +0000) Tj
T*
(Link:) Tj
T*
(https://buttondown.com/hillelwayne/archive/people-get-confused-when-language-implementations/) Tj
T*
(Take the following Python program: # x = 1, y = 2 x = 0 y = x print \([ x , y ]\) It'll print [0,) Tj
T*
(0] . If we swapped the two assignments, it'd instead print [0, 1] . Each assignment happens in) Tj
T*
(a separate temporal step. Pretty much all imperative languages behave this way. Now take the) Tj
T*
(following TLA+ snippet: \\* x = 1, y = 2 /\\ x' = 0 /\\ y' = x /\\ PrintT\( >\) This'll print > .) Tj
T*
(Unlike in imperative languages, TLA+ separates the notion of update and temporal step. We read) Tj
T*
(x' = 0 as "in the next state, x will be 0, but it still has the same value in the current) Tj
T*
(state". So in every state x and x' are essentially separate variables. As a consequence of) Tj
T*
(this, the order of statements don't matter in TLA+ semantics and swapping the two assignments) Tj
T*
(doesn't change the printed output. The language is really clever like that! This means, among) Tj
T*
(other things that there's basically no intrastep race conditions. One function can update a) Tj
T*
(variable without affecting how any other function uses it. Okay so now beginners inevitably run) Tj
T*
(into a problem with this: \\* x = 1, y = 2 /\\ x' = y' /\\ y' = x /\\ PrintT\( >\) This'll crash) Tj
T*
(because y' isn't defined yet. But if we swap the two assignments this works fine...) Tj
T*
() Tj
